Net Profit (TTM/latest) (2025-10-14): -10199000.00

Title   : Silver's white-hot rally triggers supply crisis as ETFs trade at shocking 10-15% premium 
Source  : economictimes.indiatimes.com
Published: 2025-10-14T07:37:33
Fetched : 2025-10-14T16:18:34.791391
URL     : https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/commodities/news/silvers-white-hot-rally-triggers-supply-crisis-as-etfs-trade-at-shocking-10-15-premium/articleshow/124546905.cms
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The white metal, which has delivered a scorching 70%-plus return this year and crossed the $50-an-ounce threshold for the first time ever last week, is now creating chaos in domestic markets as commodity traders acting as market makers report "low to negligible inventory" of London Bullion Market Association (LBMA)-certified silver bars—the only type regulators permit for ETF procurement.
Kotak, SBI, Tata, and UTI Mutual Fund have stopped accepting fresh lump-sum investments in their Silver ETFs as the supply crunch pushes domestic ETF prices far above international benchmarks, raising red flags about potential mark-to-market losses for investors once premiums normalise.
Bank of America has thrown fuel on the fire, raising its silver target to $65 an ounce with an average of $56.25, even as it anticipates an 11% decline in demand next year. The bank cited a continued supply shortfall, with the Silver Institute projecting the metal is on track to record its fifth consecutive year of structural market deficit.
"Silver jumped over 1.5% to above $53/oz on Tuesday, hitting fresh record highs as a historic short squeeze and tightening liquidity in London drove traders to scramble for physical supply globally," said Jigar Trivedi, Senior Research Analyst at Reliance Securities. "Lease rates in London soared more than 30% on Friday, pushing rollover costs for short positions to unsustainable levels."
Riya Singh, Research Analyst for Commodities and Currency at Emkay Global Financial Services, painted a stark picture of the global supply crisis: "Silver has surged sharply as investors rotate out of the dollar into tangible assets, reflecting mounting apprehension over U.S. fiscal stability and the autonomy of the Federal Reserve. Supply constraints have intensified, with robust shipments to the United States amid concerns of potential import tariffs draining London inventories to multi-year lows."
Singh highlighted India's pivotal role in the crisis, noting that the world's largest consumer of silver is seeing prices trade at steep premiums of 10-15% over global benchmarks. "In India, prices are trading at a steep premium driven by robust investment and festival-related demand, prompting physically backed ETFs to halt new subscriptions. Industrial and investment demand continues to outpace supply," she said.
Mirae Asset Mutual Fund issued a stark warning to investors about the dangers of buying at current elevated levels. "Due to the inventory shortage, the premium spiked in the domestic market, and higher demand made it worse. Market makers began quoting at higher levels both on screen (for ETF trading on the exchange) and off screen (for buying by ETF scheme), and investors continued to buy at elevated levels," the fund house said.
Also Read | Gold ETF inflows jump fourfold in September to Rs 8,363 crore, hit record high
The distortion has upended normal market mechanics. While MCX futures typically serve as the primary reference price for physical silver in India, with bullion traders quoting premiums or discounts relative to it for LBMA-certified bars, current supply constraints have shattered this relationship. "The current supply constraints have distorted this relationship, leading to elevated acquisition costs as premiums have gone up multi-fold over regular premiums paid," Mirae Asset noted.
The fund house warned investors to exercise extreme caution: "High premiums will increase the cost of acquiring silver ETFs. If silver prices remain stable and premiums revert to normal levels in the near future, investors may face mark-to-market losses on their ETF holdings or losses corresponding to premium compression. We suggest that investors should avoid buying silver as of now and remain watchful for a few days."
The structural supply crisis runs deep. Singh explained that over the past four years, global silver consumption has exceeded production, eroding the surplus accumulated over the preceding five years. "In 2025, supply remains constrained, as roughly 70% of silver is mined as a by-product of other metals, limiting the pace at which output can respond to higher prices. Demand from renewable energy, electronics, and high-tech sectors further intensifies the structural deficit," she said.
India's import data underscores the severity of the imbalance. In the first eight months of 2025, silver imports plunged 42% to 3,302 tons, while ETF inflows and other investment channels surged. "Consequently, manufacturers are struggling to produce silverware, coins, and bars, while festive purchases ahead of Diwali have pushed premiums higher. Investor reluctance to liquidate existing holdings has tightened scrap availability, further straining the market," Singh added.
U.S. policy developments have added another layer of pressure. Following silver's inclusion in a draft critical minerals list in September, shipments to the United States have accelerated, raising concerns over potential tariffs under Section 232 investigations covering silver, platinum, and palladium. "This uncertainty, combined with historically low London inventories, has amplified price volatility. Benchmark London prices have approached record levels, nearing $53.95 per ounce," Singh said.
Also Read | Sectoral and thematic fund inflows fall over 69% in September. Is investor appetite cooling?
The supply squeeze has become so acute that traders are resorting to extraordinary measures. "Some traders transport silver bars via air freight, a method typically reserved for gold, to exploit the London premium. Silver's smaller market size and lower liquidity relative to gold magnify these price movements," Singh noted.
Singh projects silver could maintain its upward trajectory toward 165,000-185,000-194,639 levels domestically, while internationally it could test $56-$58-$59.89, with key support around 153,195-150,000 locally and $51.85-$50 globally. However, she cautioned: "Absent a stabilising central bank bid, even modest reductions in investment inflows could trigger sharp corrections, unwinding the London tightness that has underpinned the recent rally."
Meanwhile, personal finance author and 'Rich Dad Poor Dad' fame Robert Kiyosaki has been bullish on silver, calling it and cryptocurrency Ethereum "hot, hot, hot" in a recent social media post. Kiyosaki predicted that silver could soon hit $75 per ounce, after recently crossing the $50 mark.
Bank of America acknowledged the potential for near-term volatility, noting: "There is scope for recent dislocations to slowly start to normalise, which could then also increase volatility and put pressure on silver quotations near-term."
Trivedi added that markets remained focused on US-China trade dynamics ahead of a potential Trump-Xi meeting in South Korea later this month, while expectations for another Federal Reserve quarter-point rate cut this month, followed by a likely move in December, continued to support precious metals.
(Disclaimer: Recommendations, suggestions, views and opinions given by the experts are their own. These do not represent the views of the Economic Times)
